A slang term used in Spanish to refer to foreign visitors.  Originally, guiri referred to fair-skinned Northern Europeans on package holidays (from the mid-twentieth century) but the term is now used in a more general way, referring for instance to long-term foreign residents from Northern Europe, recent immigrants from North Africa, Pakistan and Latin America, and dark-skinned travellers from the Western world.  However, the stereotype of a guiri is still a sunburned fair-haired English or American person wearing shorts, socks, sandals, sunglasses and with a camera in full view.

The term has also been adopted to some extent by long-term foreign visitors or residents in Spanish cities as a source of pride, unifying a disparate group of people for whom the only thing in common is not being Spanish.  Although originally the definition of a guiri was someone who could not speak Spanish properly or at all, many of these recent guiris have lived in Spain for many years and as Hispanophiles are conversant with Spanish language and culture.